<tr id="Strzhemechny2006300" class="entry">
	<td>Strzhemechny, M., Avdeenko, A., Eremenko, V., Pyshkin, O. and Buravtseva, L.</td>
	<td>Observation of triplet excimer emission in 2-bromobenzophenone <p class="infolinks">[<a href="javascript:toggleInfo('Strzhemechny2006300','abstract')">Abstract</a>] [<a href="javascript:toggleInfo('Strzhemechny2006300','bibtex')">BibTeX</a>]</p></td>
	<td>2006</td>
	<td><font color="#006400">Chemical Physics Letters</font><br/>Vol. 431(4-6), pp. 300-302&nbsp;</td>
	<td><a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.cplett.2006.09.097" target="_blank">DOI</a> &nbsp;</td>
</tr>
<tr id="abs_Strzhemechny2006300" class="abstract noshow">
	<td colspan="7"><b>Abstract</b>: Phosphorescence spectra of 2-bromobenzophenone (2Br-BP) crystals were measured from 70 K to room temperature. A capital crossover in the emission mechanism takes place within this temperature range, leaving at room temperature only a broad two-hump feature. Additional phosphorescence experiments, carried out to understand the nature of this spectrum, include measurements from 2Br-BP solutions in ethanol as well as time-resolved and varying-excitation-intensity measurements from crystals. Based on results of these experiments and on our own single-crystal X-ray structure data, we conclude that the above two-band spectrum recorded near room temperature is due to the emission of single-photon bi-molecular triplet excimer formed by the carbonyl groups of two neighbor 2-bromobenzophenone molecules.</td>
