	<td>Fil, V., Bezuglyi, E., Burma, N., Gaiduk, A., Kolobov, I., van Kempen, H. and Deyneka, E.</td>
	<td>Electron sound in Al <p class="infolinks">[<a href="javascript:toggleInfo('Fil19962547','abstract')">Abstract</a>] [<a href="javascript:toggleInfo('Fil19962547','bibtex')">BibTeX</a>]</p></td>
	<td>1996</td>
	<td><font color="#006400">Czechoslovak Journal of Physics</font><br/>Vol. 46(SUPPL. 5), pp. 2547-2548&nbsp;</td>
	<td><a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/BF02570260" target="_blank">DOI</a> &nbsp;</td>
</tr>
<tr id="abs_Fil19962547" class="abstract noshow">
	<td colspan="7"><b>Abstract</b>: Electron sound (ES) represents fast electron mode propagating in metals with the Fermi velocity and possessing linear dispersion law. We have measured the velocity and the amplitude of ES in AI single crystals within a wide range of temperature and magnetic field. It was discovered that in Al the electron-electron scattering yields the main contribution (~T2) in ES attenuation. In contrast to Ga and Mo, ES amplitude in the superconducting state of Al increases sharply just below Tc. The ES in Al represents most likely the sum of two signals of different nature - Fermi-liquid zero sound and ballistic quasiwaves.</td>
</tr>
