<tr id="Vorontsov197797" class="entry">
	<td>Vorontsov, S. and Svechkarev, I.</td>
	<td>Magnetic susceptibility of a two-dimensional crystal <p class="infolinks">[<a href="javascript:toggleInfo('Vorontsov197797','abstract')">Abstract</a>] [<a href="javascript:toggleInfo('Vorontsov197797','bibtex')">BibTeX</a>]</p></td>
	<td>1977</td>
	<td><font color="#006400">Sov J Low Temp Phys</font><br/>Vol. 3(2), pp. 97-99&nbsp;</td>
	<td><a href="https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-0017453353&partnerID=40&md5=afe6a9e289d38d23c09051148b1f7a6f" target="_blank">URL</a>&nbsp;</td>
</tr>
<tr id="abs_Vorontsov197797" class="abstract noshow">
	<td colspan="7"><b>Abstract</b>: The orbital magnetic susceptibility has been determined for strictly two-dimensional motion of the conduction electrons in a layered structure. Such electrons correspond to cylindrical Fermi surfaces, i. e. , the energy spectrum contains no component of the wave vector perpendicular to the layers. Expressions have been derived for the major contributions to the susceptibility for certain types of perturbation in a parabolic spectrum due to Bragg planes. Results are presented from a numerical calculation on the effects of the chemical-potential level on the orbital and spin susceptibilities for the case where there is one plane, which show that there are sharp features at the critical points in the spectrum.</td>
</tr>
<tr id="bib_Vorontsov197797" class="bibtex noshow">
